{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Events\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In this subsection, we describe how everyday users activities are visible in the A1 data stream. The events detected by the monitoring units from each terminal depends on the type of terminal. While it is not feasible to cover all events (complete list of events is shown in Tab.\u160?[tab:eventtype]), we only describe the ones (mobility related) used in our system.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Calls\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When a terminal establishes a call with another subscriber a Mobile Originated Call event is created. The receiving terminal will create a Mobile Terminated Call event. Whenever a call is ended (e.g.\u160?one subscriber hangs up)an A Disconnect event is created. However in our research of the data stream, there was no evidence of an A Disconnect event.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab MOBILE TERMINATED CALL (0x1D): terminal receives a call\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab MOBILE ORIGINATED CALL (0x22): terminal originates a call\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab A DISCONNECT (0x18): The call is closed\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Location Area Update\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Devices are most of the time in \u8220"idle\u8221" mode where they are switched on but are not involved in any voice/data communication. In this state the device must still be reachable by the network. Thus, when a terminal changes to a cell in a different location area, it sends a Location Area Update message to the core network. This message appears in the data stream as:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab LOCATION UPDATE (0x1F), in case of 2G terminal\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab IUCS LOCATION UPDATE NORMAL (0x15), in case of 3G terminal\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If a devices do not change its Location Area for a specific time and the PLAU timer expires it sends a keep alive message to the core network.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab IUPS RA PERIODIC UPDATE (0x0C) and IUCS LOC UPD PERIODIC (0x17) in case of 3G terminal (for PS and CS domain respectively)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab LOCATION UPDATE (0x1F) in case of 2G terminals\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Fig.\u160?[fig:latraversed] illustrates where a location area update (red cell) happens when a subscriber traverses different location areas on its way.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\cf1 [image: ./images/laupdate.pdf]\cf0} [fig:latraversed]\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Handover Cell Update\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When a call is established the terminal is said to be in active \u8220"connected\u8221" state (see [subsub:connected]). In this state, the network is informed about each change of cell, regardless of the LA to which the cell belongs. A limitation is that the A1 data stream is not able to capture cell changes for 3G terminals (these messages do not reach the core network, but terminate in the radio access network, i.e. they cannot be monitored by the systems). However cell changes for 2G terminals appear as:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab GB CELL CHANGE (0x02), in case of an ongoing data connection,\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab HANDOVER CELL UPDATE (0x20), in case of an ongoing call.\sa180\par}
