{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 OpenCoverageMap\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 OpenCoverageMap was a project and master thesis done by a colleague of mine at the University of Applied Science Upper Austria. Dieter Schlosser\u160? goal was to create an open network coverage map for mobile networks. Instead of relying on measurements and coverage reports handed out by network operators he was using smartphones that were doing the measurements. This approach, where users a carrying out work, is know as crowd-sourcing\u160?.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Purpose\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In our project, we are using OpenCoverageMap data to evaluate our approaches. In order to measure the network, OpenCoverageMap captures events similar to the events captured by A1. The OpenCoverageMap application which is installed on the smartphone periodically records the position (using GPS), the phone state as well as the currently connected cell site. Tab.\u160?[tab:ocmrecord] shows an example of data that was recorded by the OpenCoverageMap application.\par}
