{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Data Structure\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 OpenCoverageMap does not capture events, therefore, our systems needs to covert the OpenCoverageMap data stream to the same format as the A1 data steam. Call establishment and termination events are generated by comparing the timestamps of each record. OpenCoverageMap logs the state of the MS every second. By iterating over the records and comparing the current state with the previous one, it is possible to extract call establishment and termination events. To generate handover events, an iteration over all records is done, each record compares the cell id and lac with the previous one. If both are similar no event is generated. However, if they are different a handover event is generated. After the conversion is done the OpenCoverageMap event stream looks the same as the A1 event stream.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Voronoi Tessellation\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To generate trajectories for each mobile subscriber their coarse location is needed. For this purpose,we first need an estimation of the coverage area of all cell sites. When a mobile subscriber is connected to a cell site we know that his current position must be withing the coverage area of the cell site. A fast approximation of the coverage area can be done with Voronoi diagrams. As mentioned before Tettamanti2012 et al.\u160? used Voronoi tessellation to estimate the coverage area.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Voronoi diagrams are widely used in computer science, e.g.\u160?pattern matching, space division, cluster analysis, collision detection, etc.\u160?as mentioned by Aurenhammer\u160?.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\cf1 [image: ./images/voronoi2]\cf0} [fig:voronoi2]\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Point Tessellation\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The following assumptions are based on {\i Voronoi diagrams\u8211-a survey of a fundamental geometric data structure} by Aurenhammer\u160? {\i Computational Geometry: Algorithms and Applications} by Makr de Berg\u160?.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let {\i P}\u8196?=\u8196?\{{\i p}{\sub 1},\u8198?{\i p}{\sub 2},\u8198?...,\u8198?{\i p}{\sub {\i n}}\} be a set of {\i n} distinct points, in our case the location of each cell site. The Voronoi diagram of {\i P} is a subdivision of the plane into {\i n} cells. The property that each Voronoi cell must fulfill is that a point {\i q} lies in the cell respective to a site {\i p}{\sub {\i i}} only if {\i d}{\i i}{\i s}{\i t}({\i q},\u8198?{\i p}{\sub {\i i}})\u8196?<\u8196?{\i d}{\i i}{\i s}{\i t}({\i q},\u8198?{\i p}{\sub {\i j}}) for each {\i p}{\sub {\i j}}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i P} where {\i i}\u8196?\u8800?\u8196?{\i j}. Each cell defines the coverage area for the n-th cell site. Moreover each cell is a (possibly unbounded) open convex polygon. Fig.\u160?[fig:voronoi2] illustrates a Voronoi diagram for 16 random points in a two dimensional space. It can be seen that the outer cells are not closed, they shape an open convex polygon. In Section\u160?[sec:boundaries] we show a method to produce closed polygons.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$dist(p,q)=\\sqrt\{\\left(p_x-q_x\\right)^2+\\left(p_y-q_y\\right)^2\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Boundaries\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Voronoi diagrams are unbounded which means that the coordinates of vertices can be infinite. Unbounded polygons are undesired in a topology computation. If we would use unbounded polygons for coverage estimation, the area for this cell site would be infinite. A simple approach to eliminate this effect is to clip the Voronoi diagram with a rectangular bounding box. However, this approach is only satisfying if the cell site boundaries shape a rectangle. A better approach is to compute the convex hull over all sites and clip it with the Voronoi diagram.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Cell Tower Segmentation\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We mentioned before that a GSM network consists not only of omni directional antennas but also of sectored antennas. The coverage area of each sector is defined by the angle at which the antenna is mounted on the tower. If we would only consider the location of each cell sites, sectors with different angles would have the same Voronoi polygon and, therefore, the same coverage area. In order to get a better representation of the coverage area for each sector, we moved the location of each sector based on its angle {\i \u981?}. The definition of the movement can be found in Equation\u160?[eq:move]. The constant factor means a maximum movement of 3 meters in either direction.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$\\label\{eq:move\}
\tab x=x+\\frac\{cos(\\phi)\}\{50000\},y=y+\\frac\{cos(\\phi)\}\{50000\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Trajectory Generation Pipeline\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In this chapter, the pipeline to generate trajectories for mobile subscribers is introduced. The developed pipeline consists of a five-steps model, which is shown in Figure\u160?[fig:pipeline]. The concept to generate trajectories is the following: The input data is iteratively used to generate trajectories for each subscriber. The output is a trajectory which consists of the route, traveled by the subscriber as well as timestamps, which defines the point in time when the subscriber was located at this location. Given below each step of the pipeline is described in more detail to better understand how the system operates.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\cf1 [image: ./images/pipeline]\cf0} [fig:pipeline]\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Input Data\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This section focuses on input data that is consumed by the system. The gathering of input data is the first step in the developed pipeline. Moreover input data can be distinguished between four data types, which are used by the system: geographical data, socio-statistical data, mobile subscription data (A1 and OCM), road network data. The different data types are described in the succeeding sections.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Geographical Input Data\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As mentioned before GSM does not expose an accurate location of the subscriber. In GSM, only the Cell-ID of the current connected cell is known. However, to calculate a route between the start and end of the call a more accurate location is needed. Because the coverage area of cell can be from as little as 500{\i m}{\super 2} up to 50{\i k}{\i m}{\super 2}, boundaries need to be set in which subscribers can be located. The assumption is that the majority of subscribers will start or end their journey in an urban fabric whereas only a small fraction of subscribers will start or end their journey in open land. In the course of this project the geographic information is derived from data from the {\i CORINE}{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 CORINE: \u8220"Coordination of Information on the Environment\u8221"; {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.eea.europa.\line
eu/publications/COR0-landcover"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
http://www.eea.europa.
eu/publications/COR0-landcover
}}}
, last accessed on March 11,2014\par}
} project which was initiated by the European Commission in 1985. The main purpose of this project was to generate a geographic information system for the member states of the European Union. The {\i CORINE} land cover (CLC) project is one essential part of the {\i CORINE} projects which aim to develop a land cover information system for twelve member states of the European Union (Effective 2006). The {\i CORINE} land cover project distinguishes between five main categories and in total 44 land cover classes. Out of the five only two categories are applicable for the purpose of defining boundaries where a subscriber can be located: {\i artificial surfaces} and {\i agricultural areas}. The three remaining categories \u8211-{\i forest and semi-natural areas}, {\i wetlands} and {\i water bodies}\u8211- can be considered as areas where subscribers are not starting or ending their calls. The {\i CORINE} land cover data for Austria can be obtained from the following service{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.data.gv.at/datensatz/?id=9246f37d-da69-4442-9504-ebd006a059bb"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
http://www.data.gv.at/datensatz/?id=9246f37d-da69-4442-9504-ebd006a059bb
}}}
, last accessed on March 11,2014\par}
}. The land cover data is provided in two different data types, first as a raster image with a grid size of 100 meters and second as a Shapefile..Figure\u160?[fig:clc{\sub a}ustria] illustrates the land cover map{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Image source: {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.eea.europa.eu/data-and-maps/figures/corine-land-cover-2000-by-country/clc00_at_national.eps/image_original"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
